==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dorian
<hw>Do"ri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or
pertaining to the ancient Greeks of Doris; Doric; <as>as, a
<ex>Dorian</ex> fashion</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Same as <er>Doric</er>, 3.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Dorian</xex> mood.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dorian mode</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>the first of
the authentic church modes or tones, from D to D, resembling our D minor
scale, but with the B natural.</cd> <rj><au>Grove.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dorian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dorian
<hw>Do"ri*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A native or inhabitant of Doris in
Greece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Doric</ent>⟦br⟧
